b'Today, @Nasdaq filed a proposal with the SEC that would require the boards of directors of #NasdaqListed companies to have, or explain why they do not have, at least two diverse directors and regularly disclose diversity statistics.
 
Via this proposal, @Nasdaq will:
:check_mark: Build a framework for companies to recruit diverse candidates for board positions and provide investors with greater transparency on corporate governance.
:check_mark: Require companies to have, or explain why they do not have, at least two diverse board directors: one who self-identifies as female and one who self-identifies as either an underrepresented minority or LGBTQ+.
:check_mark: Equip companies with the resources necessary to successfully address board composition planning challenges, with new partner and provider of corporate leadership data solutions, Equilar Inc.
 
Learn how we are working to drive greater transparency on corporate governance via the #LinkInBio \xe2\x80\x94and scroll through for some thoughts from Nasdaq\xe2\x80\x99s leadership.'

b'@Nasdaq continues #AmplifyingBlackVoices, a multimedia retrospective featuring works of art documenting Black life.

@love4rico, a self-taught artist from Brooklyn, makes storytelling imagery that combines color and passion while documenting everyday life around the world. He also runs @the.yenhouse, a multidisciplinary creative company that aims to shift the perspective in which people see creatives and their creations.\xc2\xa0

Last month, his artwork was broadcast on the @Nasdaq tower in Times Square.

\xe2\x80\x9cAll shot in Africa, these images show the Art in everyday life in the motherland. I chose to display these because they amplify the Black Voices of those all over the world, they show the beauty in simple things.\xe2\x80\x9d

Head to the #LinkInBio and @love4rico\xe2\x80\x99s profile to learn more about his work.'

b'@Nasdaq continues #AmplifyingBlackVoices, a multimedia retrospective featuring works of art documenting Black life.

@bestofrae is a self-taught artist and UX designer based in Washington, DC. She works as a freelancer and designer, and contributes her talent to social change causes and movements.

Last month, four pieces of her artwork were broadcast on the @Nasdaq tower in Times Square. Her artwork represents an under looked aspect of Black womanhood.\xc2\xa0

\xe2\x80\x9cIn the movement, Black women often get overlooked, and when we are praised, it is for our strength and toughness. But we should be valued for our softness as well. We are still valid in our moments of peace and happiness that are unattached to a struggle. And I wanted to capture those moments as well.\xe2\x80\x9d

Head to the #LinkInBio and @bestofrae\xe2\x80\x99s profile to learn more about her work.'

b'@Nasdaq continues #AmplifyingBlackVoices, a multimedia retrospective featuring works of art documenting Black life.

@pollyirungu is the founder of @BlackWomenPhotographers, a community and online database of Black women photographers. Irungu is a multimedia journalist, digital editor and photographer herself.\xc2\xa0

Last week her artwork was broadcast on the @Nasdaq tower in Times Square.\xc2\xa0

\xe2\x80\x9cI chose these photos to showcase Black women in all of their glory. I want members of my @BlackWomenPhotographers community to remember their power, their joy, and to never forget who they are. I want these photos to serve as a reminder to never dim your light or shrink and change yourself for anything or anyone.\xe2\x80\x9d

Head to the #LinkInBio and @pollyirungu\xe2\x80\x99s Instagram profile to learn more about her work.'

b'At Nasdaq, we celebrate moments in history that help advance society and  #RewriteTomorrow. :rocket: Today we recognize @NASA\xe2\x80\x99s 50th anniversary of the Apollo 13 launch, a critical mission for the safe return of its crew in spite of a catastrophic explosion.

On the mission was Commander James Lovell Jr., Command Module Pilot John Swigert Jr. and Lunar Module Pilot Fred Haise Jr. When an oxygen tank in the Apollo service module ruptured, experts in the Apollo Mission Control Center immediately focused their efforts on bringing the crew back safely. Splashdown occurred in the Pacific Ocean at 1:07 p.m. April 17, 1970.
.
\xe2\x80\x9cOur goal 50 years ago was to save our valiant crew after sending them around the Moon and return them safely to Earth,\xe2\x80\x9d said NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine. \xe2\x80\x9cOur goal now is to return to the Moon to stay, in a sustainable way.\xe2\x80\x9d Learn how @NASA is marking the Apollo 13 anniversary digitally via our #LinkInBio. :crescent_moon:'

.

b'In 1906, entrepreneur Madam CJ Walker created a hair care line that would propel her to become the first American woman to be a self-made millionaire. After finding that she had a hair disorder that caused her to lose much of her hair, the founder created the Madame C.J. Walker Laboratories to treat Black hair. Not only did she sell product, she also opened a beauty school and was a civil rights activist.\n\nHer company became very well-known for not only its successful sales, but also for introducing educational and philanthropic efforts within the African American community. \xe2\x80\x9cI am not satisfied in making money for myself,\xe2\x80\x9d she said about her career. \xe2\x80\x9cI endeavor to provide employment for hundreds of the women of my race.\xe2\x80\x9d #BlackHistoryMonth'

b'Guy Bluford was first accepted to NASA\xe2\x80\x99s program in 1978. Little did he know he would end up making history as the first African American person to go to space.
